reviewText: Overall, I did learn some things of interest in this presentation.  T​he PFA  session leaders need to apply greater rigor to the conclusions they convey.  For example, despite the numerous statments in sthe sessions made about the hazards of PFAs in the environment, I did not hear a single hard fact about PFAs being clearly connected to any particular health outcome at either a mechanistic or laboratory level.  No animal studies. No laboratory studies.   No clear mechanistic connection to a particular negaive human health outcome.   So these sessions sounded more faith-based than scientific.
